[00:00:00]

What's going on crafters, Khalil here back again and in this video we're going to talk about why software development is so freaking hard and it's about these three roles and their goals.

So there's this interesting thing called game theory. It's a study of how and why we make decisions. And they apply this to any sort of dynamic where there's active agents, different actors who are going in, playing a game, trying to get resources, trying to win something, and effectively they're trying to move to some sort of goal.

And strategy gets introduced when you have multiple roles with multiple goals, and They're all contending to get to their goals. So if we think of chess, of course, it is a two player game, And you want to checkmate your opponent.

Now if we think of software development and everyone involved, it actually is a team sport, however there are other elements that we [00:01:00] have to be aware of that will make it very hard for us to win that game.

There's contending elements.

What's the status and the structure and the maintainability of the code base that we're currently working with? What's the market look like? What's the competition out there look like? How much time do we have? What's the skill level of the developers on our team? All these contending elements make things difficult, but we also have assistive elements as well.

And we'll talk about those a little bit more moving forward, but ultimately, the three roles that we're dealing with are users, customers, and developers. These three roles come together and create this game or this Broadway play of software development.

So in this video, what we are going to cover is what the three roles are and how their goals interplay.

The key developer use cases that you have to carry out as a developer, and we're going to finally talk about scalability and how one can achieve it.

Because that is a massive part of what we are trying to [00:02:00] do here as software developers, who are trying to get better at our craft.

So now the three roles and their goals.

We already talked about users and we learned that what they want is to get time back or to have their time enriched.

Now the other two, customers, what customers care about is increasing revenue or protecting revenue, essentially making money and saving money. And then there is the developer.

We have this really interesting dynamic where we want to help the users and the customers succeed. So we want to help them achieve their goals.

But we also want to do this in such a way that it is very easy for us to work and carry out our use cases as developers. So we get compensated when we keep the user in benefit and we keep the customer in benefit. And we simultaneously need to achieve that and set up the situation where it's very easy for us to continually.

do our work to keep them in benefit. So all of that comes together and I've put it into a bit of an image here to [00:03:00] better describe this.

Coming back to it, the thing we're trying to do here is to create software artifacts of value. And it's interesting because we have to do this work that is going to benefit both the users and the customers at the same time.

Now, in order for us to do that, we primarily carry out our work against this concept of features.

We're going to expand on this a little bit more moving forward. This is gonna get into one of the essentials, namely the vertical slicing essential. But we do our work against features.

So our task is to not only discover and understand features in a code base, like if you're going to step into a new one, You need to make it very easy for yourself and other developers to understand what the features are, what the app can do.

You also need to be able to test features and extend them, change them, add new features, debug features. These are the sort of building blocks that software artifacts of value are made from. They are [00:04:00] made from features.

And if we could carry out our key developer use cases in such a way that we keep both the user and the customer in benefit at the same time, then we are succeeding at our task.

Now to do this means that we need to work with extremely effective mental models that are going to closely align with all three goals at the same time.

To just really highlight how difficult this is,

let's say the goal is, how can I make a thousand dollars by the end of the month? There's a lot of different ways to do that, but as soon as you add in a new goal, a new constraint, it makes it a lot harder for you to achieve that goal.

So how can I achieve 1, 000 at the end of the month as a clown technician? I don't really know what a clown technician is, just made that up. But how could I achieve 1, 000 by the end of the month as a, let's say, landscaper? That is going to constrain down the set of things that you could possibly do to achieve that goal.[00:05:00]

So really we are working with three different sets of goals that are coming together into one.

And scalability is the word that best describes what it is we're trying to achieve as the apex of all three of those goals.

So things we need to watch out for in order to do this are bugs, defects, regressions, missing requirements, incomplete implementations, features taking longer and longer to build, this one hits close to home, that is my experience, and code bases that are harder and harder to change over time. Yeah, been there.

All of this is negative value. It's moving from benefit from a good place to a bad place. So we want to avoid this as much as possible, which means we need to introduce mental models that are closely aligned with reality, that are going to help us avoid negative value.
